This was working in 2.8.2 but this data is no longer logged in 2.9.2 or 2.10.1:

{noformat}
2013-02-11 10:52:38,322 INFO  [main ] fisheye.app SystemResourceMonitor-<init> - Max File Descriptors = 4096
{noformat}

Find the feature here:
https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/FE-4218

Currently, the Code Metrics Report is only for a single week.

{quote}
What management is looking to do is leverage this and extend to allow for aggregate or cumulative reports for this information. For example, Code Metrics from Date1 to Date2, or Month to Month, or Q1, Q2, etc.

Even better would be able to generate these dynamically instead of you providing us with the fixed interval of reporting.
{quote}

If I use this smart commit:
{noformat}
Editing file +review CR @admin @user1
{noformat}
The review is created and the users {{admin}} and {{user1}} are correctly added to the review.

However, if I add a punctuation character, like this:
{noformat}
Editing file again +review CR @admin @user1.
{noformat}

The review is created, but only the user {{admin}} is added to the review. Due to the period character next to the username, the user {{user1}} is not recognized as a valid user.

h3.Steps to reproduce:
# Create a folder in SVN:
{noformat}
svn mkdir testfolder
svn add testfolder
svn commit -m 'new testfolder'
{noformat}
# Look for the folder at {{FishEye Source >> <repo_name>}}
# Enable the option [Hide empty directories|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/FISHEYE/Browsing+through+a+repository#Browsingthrougharepository-hide]

The ability to change all user's auth type would be useful when moving from "built-in" authentication to LDAP.

As a workaround we are currently executing the following SQL command against the FishEye database:

UPDATE fisheye.cru_user set cru_authtype=2;

{quote}
Our setup has multiple Jira projects (one for each development "pod" on our team) that work against a single code repository. We manually match versions across these projects for most of our reporting within Jira (ie, FixVersions of "5.22 September Release" exists across all our projects"). I have been asked to see if I can generate a report/dashboard to show the review coverage for a single release (ie, across this defined list of Jira projects against the single repository). We are wanting to see what percentage of our code that goes for a single release (ie, version) has been reviewed. 
{quote}

{quote}
The Release Report gives us more or less the "negative view" of what we want - ie, it tells us which jira cards have a code review, but it doesn't give us all the cards that are in the release that do not have a code review (which is ultimately what we are driving towards). 
{quote}

FishEye/Crucible uses a lot of file handles. Make it easy for users to tell how many file handles are in use and how many the application registers as maximum by displaying this data in {{Administration}}. This information is already now automatically logged upon startup in the logs:


{noformat}
